	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>The WTO fisheries subsidies negotiations: views from Barbados </h1>

			
			<h4>
												02 July 2009
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>Subsidy Watch (SW) recently published an interview with representatives of the permanent missions of Barbados and New Zealand in Geneva on disciplining fisheries subsidies. For Barbados small-island developing-country fisheries are a possible growth sector, and ‘we, as traditional under-exploiters of our natural resources, must be able to develop. Therefore, while we recognise the sustainability element of the discussion and respect it, we also have a developmental angle which is equally important.’ </p><p>Those countries with a history of extensive subsidisation and over exploitation should be those most highly disciplined in the fisheries subsidies negotiations, according to Barbados. Countries like Barbados, with small fleets and a high dependence on fisheries as a source of employment, nutrition and food security, should have minimal disciplines imposed. </p><p>On whether or not S&amp;DT should allow subsidies for small-scale fishing for all members or for developing countries only, Barbados feels that if flexibility is accorded to the small-scale fishers in developed countries ‘we would expect even more flexibility - a complete exemption from the disciplines for example - for our fleets’. </p><p>On permitted subsidies, the key is to enhance the notification and monitoring process to make it responsive should permitted subsidies become the cause of over-fishing. Such rules should not put those who cause the least damage at a disadvantage: the smallest and most vulnerable amongst the members of the WTO. This applies also to fisheries-management plans. While the idea has merit, it is the greatest subsidisers that have already established fisheries-management plans. </p><p>Those countries that will need the greatest technical assistance in developing their fisheries-management systems would be the small developing countries of the small and vulnerable economies (SVEs) and the ACP - the prime countries which do not deserve to have onerous restrictions placed on their potential to develop their industry.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
<i>Subsidy Watch</i>, interview, May 2009<br/>
<a href="http://www.globalsubsidies.org/en/subsidy-watch/analysis/the-wto-fisheries-negotiations-interviews-with-barbados-and-new-zealand" target="_self">http://www.globalsubsidies.org/en/subsidy-watch/analysis/the-wto-fisheri...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Small-scale fisheries, and S&amp;DT are potentially a major stumbling block on reaching agreement in the fishery-subsidy negotiations. At one level, defining the size and scope of small-scale fishing operations is a highly contentious issue, particularly if physical size is taken as the main criterion. Defining small-scale fishing should transcend physical size and fishing capacity; it should seek to incorporate and otherwise make explicit the economic and social linkages that make small-scale fishing so vital to the economies, to food-and-livelihood security, and to the social fabric and cultural traditions of coastal communities, particularly in developing countries.</p><p>At another level, as shown here, small-scale fisheries may prove to be a bone of contention between the developing and developed countries. Clearly S&amp;DT should apply to developing countries that cause the ‘least damage’ and have the greatest needs, and not to those countries that are the greatest subsidisers and which have the greatest potential to cause overfishing.</p>
		</div>
		
